Observation Details: Don DesJardin and I found this bird early in the scrubby area northwest of the parking lot along the boundary with the wastewater plant. I was en-route to checking the restoration area where the bird had been seen previously, but Don and I ran into one another on the trail along the channel and decided to check this particular area as there was bird activity there. The Verdin popped up into view 5-10 minutes after we started searching that area. It was initially quiet, but began vocalizing frequently thereafter. I stayed around to help other birders get on it and I saw the bird on-and-off for 2-3 hours. During that period, it eventually moved to the restoration site near Tsumas Creek. Based on the extent of yellow on the head, I suspect this is an adult female. Small gray tit with a dull yellow face and small dark-red shoulder patch.

Observation Details: Small gray passerine superficially like Bushtit but paler. Darker brownish gray primaries and tail. Dull yellow chin, face and crown. Red lesser coverts produced a narrow wing bar at the bend of the folded wing. Legs and feet were dark gray. Bill was dark gray and longer and more pointed than that of Bushtit. Gave hard, dry "kit" calls when it took flight from one spot to another.

Observation Details: Photo taken by Larry Friesen on 22 December 2003. Bird may have remained till 6 January 2004.  A lone pine tree is the center of the area where the bird hangs out.  I first saw it to the S and W of the pine tree (N 34.45664 W 119.76493) in California sage.  The problem is that the bird tumbles further to the E down into the steep E-facing scrub that is Christian School property to the E of San Marcos Foothills. The bird called several times and that was helpful in relocating it.  The call we heard was a short, rapid, monotonal twittering.

Observation Details: Small bird. Pale gray overall. Short, stout, but sharply pointed bill; yellow/bicolored bill of juvenile; strong legs/feet. Bill shape and color, especially, would seem to rule out juvenile Lucy's Warbler. Also, this bird has a higher, more rounded head than the comparatively flat-headed warbler. See 2 comparable photos at https://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/Verdin/id

Observation Details: When I started this checklist, I found the Verdin calling near Perkins Road along the fenceline with the wastewater plant. It was almost the first bird I found. After checking other parts of the lagoon for over an hour, I later heard the Verdin further west along the fenceline and eventually saw it grabbing plant material and flying into the wastewater plant. It did this repeatedly so one can only speculate what it is doing. Someone suggested they will nest build during the winter and may use it to roost in. Too bad there is not access to the wastewater plant.

Observation Details: I initially saw this bird foraging in the trees in a similar fashion as a migrating warblers. I noticed that there was a sharp, small bill so that ruled out goldfinches. Observation Details: After many hours of searching over the past week, we finally managed to get good views of the Verdin that has been wintering in the Myoporum hedge on the south side of the railroad tracks about 600 meters east of Sand Point Road. Unlike the kinglets and warblers, this bird moved slowly and deliberately as it investigated the curled leaves, apparently in search of the thrips that were found inside. This bird called several times over the half-hour that we had it under observation, each time giving either single, sharp "chips" or series of these notes strung together. I think Dave's impression that the chip was intermediate in quality between the call of a Yellow Warbler and that of an Anna's Hummingbird was an accurate one.  This was a small bird with a wedge-shaped bill, a rounded head, a plump body, short wings, and a long tail.  I thought the short bill tapered from a relatively heavy base to a sharply pointed tip along a culmen that appeared to be almost straight, but I failed to note the length of the bill relative to field-marks on the face.  The head was smoothly rounded but unremarkable in size, and the neck was short and inconspicuous.  I thought the body was plump and that the wings were short and rounded, yet the long tail gave this bird an elongate appearance.  I was unable to determine the primary projection; however, I was able to note that it was quite short and that the wingtips were broadly pointed.  The tail was at least as long as the body, but it may have been closer to the length of the head and body combined.  More clearly evident was that the tail flared somewhat from a narrow base to a weakly notched tip.  The legs were unremarkable in their length, yet the feet seemed large for such a small bird.  This bird's patterns and coloration were relatively subtle even though the yellow head contrasted conspicuously with the gray that characterized most of the rest of the bird.  As far as I could determine, the forehead, crown, nape, sides of the head, and throat were a reasonably bright shade of lemon-yellow.  I have probably seen more brightly colored Verdins than this one, but I have also seen duller ones, and the yellow on this bird's head did seem to extend back at least to the nape and through the face.  I cannot now recall seeing the back of the neck, but the back and scapulars were medium-gray and unmarked.  I did notice at least some suggestion of chestnut at the shoulder and I suspect this color was on either the lesser or (probably more likely) the median coverts, but I could not be sure which (if not both).  The greater coverts were dark gray with diffuse tips of a paler gray shade.  I was not sure if the paler color of the tips extended up along the edges of the these feathers, yet I suspect it probably did, at least to a degree.  The remiges were also dark gray, but they had a somewhat frosted appearance that I suspect reflected paler edges.  I did not notice any obvious contrast between the wings and the upperside of the tail, but I also did not see the tail particularly well.  Below the yellow throat, the breast, belly, sides, flanks, and undertail coverts were uniformly gray, and at least a shade paler than that which characterized the upperparts.  The underside of the tail was dark gray and seemingly unmarked.  Both the bill and eyes appeared to be black, but I thought the legs were more of a dark, slaty-gray to blackish rather than being truly black.

I first saw it to the S and W of the pine tree (N 34.45664 W 119.76493) in California sage.  The problem is that the bird tumbles further to the E down into the steep E-facing scrub that is Christian School property to the E of San Marcos Foothills. The bird called several times and that was helpful in relocating it.  The call we heard was a short, rapid, monotonal twittering.

Observation Details: Small gray passerine superficially like Bushtit but paler. Darker brownish gray primaries and tail. Dull yellow chin, face and crown. Red lesser coverts produced a narrow wing bar at the bend of the folded wing. Legs and feet were dark gray. Bill was dark gray and longer and more pointed than that of Bushtit. Gave hard, dry "kit" calls when it took flight from one spot to another.

Observation Details: Found yesterday by Brian Sandstrom. Today by Thomas Wurster. Yellow appeared brightest in the front of face and chin but yellow continues around the head except at nape (gray). Black lore and sharp bill. Light gray-white belly, medium gray back/wings. Rufous epaulets (lesser coverts) evident. Alula appears black. Medium-short dark gray tail. Calling a very rapid, dry, continuous kit-kit-kit-kit-kit-kit-kit-kit…Found along the hillsides (in cactus, bushes, trees) and just below the cliff  running SW from the twin Parkside (Cattail) Ponds for about 500 feet towards the Brightwater bridge that crosses the Wintersburg Channel. Observation Details: After many hours of searching over the past week, we finally managed to get good views of the Verdin that has been wintering in the Myoporum hedge on the south side of the railroad tracks about 600 meters east of Sand Point Road. Unlike the kinglets and warblers, this bird moved slowly and deliberately as it investigated the curled leaves, apparently in search of the thrips that were found inside. This bird called several times over the half-hour that we had it under observation, each time giving either single, sharp "chips" or series of these notes strung together. I think Dave's impression that the chip was intermediate in quality between the call of a Yellow Warbler and that of an Anna's Hummingbird was an accurate one.  This was a small bird with a wedge-shaped bill, a rounded head, a plump body, short wings, and a long tail.  I thought the short bill tapered from a relatively heavy base to a sharply pointed tip along a culmen that appeared to be almost straight, but I failed to note the length of the bill relative to field-marks on the face.  The head was smoothly rounded but unremarkable in size, and the neck was short and inconspicuous.  I thought the body was plump and that the wings were short and rounded, yet the long tail gave this bird an elongate appearance.  I was unable to determine the primary projection; however, I was able to note that it was quite short and that the wingtips were broadly pointed.  The tail was at least as long as the body, but it may have been closer to the length of the head and body combined.  More clearly evident was that the tail flared somewhat from a narrow base to a weakly notched tip.  The legs were unremarkable in their length, yet the feet seemed large for such a small bird.  This bird's patterns and coloration were relatively subtle even though the yellow head contrasted conspicuously with the gray that characterized most of the rest of the bird.  As far as I could determine, the forehead, crown, nape, sides of the head, and throat were a reasonably bright shade of lemon-yellow.  I have probably seen more brightly colored Verdins than this one, but I have also seen duller ones, and the yellow on this bird's head did seem to extend back at least to the nape and through the face.  I cannot now recall seeing the back of the neck, but the back and scapulars were medium-gray and unmarked.  I did notice at least some suggestion of chestnut at the shoulder and I suspect this color was on either the lesser or (probably more likely) the median coverts, but I could not be sure which (if not both).  The greater coverts were dark gray with diffuse tips of a paler gray shade.  I was not sure if the paler color of the tips extended up along the edges of the these feathers, yet I suspect it probably did, at least to a degree.  The remiges were also dark gray, but they had a somewhat frosted appearance that I suspect reflected paler edges.  I did not notice any obvious contrast between the wings and the upperside of the tail, but I also did not see the tail particularly well.  Below the yellow throat, the breast, belly, sides, flanks, and undertail coverts were uniformly gray, and at least a shade paler than that which characterized the upperparts.  The underside of the tail was dark gray and seemingly unmarked.  Both the bill and eyes appeared to be black, but I thought the legs were more of a dark, slaty-gray to blackish rather than being truly black.
